          "title": "Separation and holiness — Israel's identity as enacted theology",
          "body": "The chapter's climax (20:26) states the deepest rationale for every law in it: 'I have set you apart from the peoples to be Mine.' Election is the ground of obligation. Israel is not holy in order to earn belonging; Israel belongs (by God's act of separation) and therefore is to be holy. This is the New Testament's logic as well — 1 Peter 2:9-12 addresses the church as 'a holy nation, a people for God's own possession,' calling them to abstain from fleshly lusts precisely because they have been called out of darkness. The dietary distinction of 20:25 is the chapter's most surprising move: the daily practice of distinguishing clean from unclean animals is a bodily, habitual enactment of Israel's separateness from the nations. Every meal is a parable of election. Gordon Wenham observes that the purity system of Leviticus creates a 'symbolic universe' in which Israel's entire life — food, sex, worship, family — is ordered to display the character of the God who called them. Leviticus 20 is not a primitive legal code awaiting moral evolution; it is a theology of divine character pressed into communal practice."
